@node "Introduction" "Switch 1.2 Introduction"
@next "Usage"
@prev "MAIN"

@{b}What is Switch?@{ub}

Switch is an Intuition based metric conversion utility.  It can be
used to convert between most common metric and British measures.  It
can also convert between Fahrenheit and Centigrade temperatures.


@{b}How to install Switch@{ub}

Drag the icon to whereever you want to put it, on hard- or
floppy-disk.  Switch is not reliant on any disk-based libraries or
support files.

Switch uses GadTools gadgets and menus, and thus requires AmigaOS
release 2.00 or above (Exec version 36 or above).  Switch has been
tested on machines running AmigaOS release 2.04, 3.0 and 3.1.


Next section: @{"The Main Window" link "Usage" 0}

@endnode


@node "Usage" "Switch 1.2 Usage"
@next "Scrollback"
@prev "Introduction"
Previous section: @{"Introduction" link "Introduction" 0}


@{b}How to run Switch@{ub}

Double-click its icon, or type "switch" in a Shell window.  Switch
does not rely on the Shell for input and output, so you may safely run
it in the background; try something like
run <>NIL: switch


@{b}Switch's Main Window@{ub}

Once Switch is running, you will see its window; there are three
points of interest:
1. The conversion indicator;
2. The input gadget;
3. The result indicator.

The conversion indicator shows the conversion which has currently been
selected.  The default is "Inches -> Centimetres".  You can select a
different conversion from the menu bar.  The menu "Conversion" has
three sub-menus: "Distance/Area", "Mass/Volume", and "Temperature".
As soon as you make a selection from the menu, the conversion
indicator will be updated.

The input gadget is simply a string gadget; it will accept letters,
but these obviously do not give a meaningful conversion!  You should
enter an integer or decimal fraction with no leading spaces.  When you
press RETURN, the conversion will be carried out and the result
displayed in the result indicator.

You can quit from the program by clicking on the window's close
gadget, or by selecting "Quit" from the "Project" menu.  Selecting
"About..."  from the "Project" menu brings up the ubiquitous
information window.  The "Scrollback" option on the Project menu
toggles the @{"scrollback window" link "Scrollback" 0}.

When the input gadget is not selected, the following keyboard
shortcuts are available:

Right Amiga-B: same as selecting "Scrollback" from the "Project" menu;
Right Amiga-?: same as selecting "About..." from the "Project" menu;
RETURN: automatically selects the input gadget for you.
Right Amiga-Q: same as selecting "Quit" from the "Project" menu;
ESCAPE: same as selecting "Quit" from the "Project" menu;

Switch's behaviour can be altered by means of @{"tooltypes" link "Tooltypes" 0}.


Next section: @{"The Scrollback Window" link "Scrollback" 0}

@endnode


@node "Scrollback" "Switch 1.2's Scrollback"
@next "Tooltypes"
@prev "Usage"
Previous section: @{"The Main Window" link "Usage" 0}


@{b}The Scrollback Window@{ub}

Switch has the ability to store the results of the last 100
conversions that were made.  The scrollback window is your interface
to this buffer.

When the scrollback is open, every time you make a conversion, it will
be added to the listview in the window.  You can use the scroll gadget
in the window to scroll back through the conversions which you've made
(hence the name :-)  Conversions will not be added to the buffer when
the scrollback is not open.

The scrollback window has five buttons attatched; these are:

@{u}Delete First@{uu}
Deletes the first item in the scrollback.
If you fill the scrollback buffer (do 100 conversions), and then do a
further conversion, Switch will automatically delete the first item in
the buffer to make space for a new one.

@{u}Delete Last@{uu}
Deletes the last item in the scrollback.

@{u}Delete All@{uu}
Clears the scrollback.
WARNING!  There's no undo.  Be sure you really want to do this!

@{u}Print@{uu}
Dumps the contents of the scrollback to your Preferences printer.  The
first time you press Print, Switch will open the printer.device.  It
will not close the printer.device until you quit the program.  The
print routine has a sixty-second timeout; if there's some sort of I/O
error, then your machine won't hang indefinitly; just wait a few
seconds and Switch will abort the transfer.  (Techie note: I wrote a
function called DoIOSafely() to do the I/O with timeout; if you want a
copy of the HS Pascal source for it, contact me and I'll send it to
you).

@{u}Insert Blank@{uu}
Inserts a blank line into the scrollback.  This is for formatting
printed conversions.  The blank line will be appended to the bottom of
the scrollback, and will take up the same space in the buffer as one
conversion (ie if you have 25 blank lines, you can only have 75
conversions).  The blank line will appear in the window as "--", but
will be printed as a blank line.

You can close the scrollback window in one of three ways:
Ę Clicking the scrollback window's Close gadget;
Ę Pressing ESCAPE in the scrollback window;
Ę Selecting the Scrollback menu item (or keyboard shortcut) in the
  main window.


Next section: @{"Preferences" link "Tooltypes" 0}

@endnode


@node "Tooltypes" "Switch 1.2 Tooltypes"
@next "Limitations"
@prev "Scrollback"
Previous section: @{"The scrollback window" link "Scrollback" 0}


@{b}Customizing Switch@{ub}

Switch responds to three icon tooltypes, which alter its behaviour;

@{u}TOPAZ@{uu}
Switch is font-adaptive, and will happily use most screen fonts up to
20pt.  Over 20pt, Switch will not try to adapt, and will use Topaz 8pt
instead.  You can override Switch's font adaptation, and force it to
use Topaz 8pt all the time, by setting the TOPAZ tooltype.

@{u}AUTOACTIVATE@{uu}
You may find it convenient to have Switch automatically activate the
input gadget for you after a menu selection, and whenever Switch's
window becomes active.  Setting the AUTOACTIVATE tooltype does just
this.  In addition, when this tooltype is set, the input gadget will
stay selected after each conversion has taken place, removing the need
to press RETURN or click in the gadget to reselect it.

@{u}NOSCROLLBACK@{uu}
This tooltype determines whether or not Switch will have its
scrollback window open initially.  By default, it does.  Setting this
tooltype will disable initial opening of the scrollback.


Next section: @{"Limitations" link "Limitations" 0}

@endnode


@node "Limitations" "Switch 1.2 Bugs and Limitations"
@next "Acknowledgements"
@prev "Tooltypes"
Previous section: @{"Preferences" link "Tooltypes" 0}


@{b}Bugs and Limitations@{ub}

The conversions are not always very accurate.  Do not use for
precision work!  They are accurate enough for day-to-day use.  They
are as accurate as the conversion tables printed in pocket diaries,
and should be used accordingly.

The font-adaptation is not always successful; this is inevitable as
there will always be someone using a really weird font that Switch
can't handle.  The TOPAZ @{"tooltype" link "Tooltypes" 0} has been provided for this purpose.

The "Delete All" @{"scrollback" link "Scrollback" 0} function really needs an "are you sure"
requester.

The scrollback functions are somewhat limited.  For example, some
people might find the fact that you cannot delete an item from the
middle of the buffer rather annoying.  The scrollback will get an
overhaul sometime in the future; features I might add include:
Ę Ability to delete any item;
Ę Ability to insert a blank line anywhere;
Ę Saving the buffer for use in a future session.


Next section: @{"Acknowledgements" link "Acknowledgements" 0}

@endnode


